      "description": "IGF::OT::IGF  NASA RESEARCH ANNOUNCEMENT AWARD FOR EFFORT TITLED:   DIRECT IMAGING AND INTERFEROMETRY OF PROTOPLANETS AT THE EPOCH OF DISK CLEANING THE MAIN GOAL OF THIS RESEARCH EFFORT IS TO EXTEND IMAGING STUDIES TO MID-IR WAVELENGTHS WHERE PLANET CANDIDATES MAY BE FOUND WITHIN WIDE OR ANNULAR GAPS IN THE DISKS, OR IN SMALL SPIRAL STRUCTURES, WHICH ARE LOCAL HOTSPOTS IN THEIR DISKS. THE CONTRACTOR WILL PERFORM HIGH ANGULAR RESOLUTION IMAGERY AND INTERFEROMETRY OF THESE DISKS, EXTENDING OBSERVATIONS TO MUCH SMALLER SPATIAL SCALES THAN COULD BE REACHED BEFORE, INTO THE TERRESTRIAL PLANET FORMING ZONE WITHIN A FEW AU OF THE HOST STAR. ARCHIVAL DATA WILL BE USED AND THE IMAGERY COMPARED WITH SPECTROSCOPIC OBSERVATIONS OF MOLECULAR GAS TO CONSTRAIN CAVITY SIZES AND IDENTIFY PLANETS, WHICH MAY HAVE CIRCUMPLANETARY DISKS. THE CONTRACTOR WILL PERFORM NEW OBSERVATIONS IN THESE BANDS USING NEW POWERFUL INSTRUMENTS INCLUDING THE LARGE BINOCULAR TELESCOPE INTERFEROMETER (LBTI), AND LMIRCAM AT THE LBTO, THE MAGAO SYSTEM AT THE MAGELLAN TELESCOPE, AND STARTING IN THE SECOND YEAR OF THE PROPOSED EFFORT, THE MULTI-APERTURE MID-INFRARED SPECTROSCOPIC EXPERIMENT (MATISSE) INSTRUMENT. MATISSE SIMULTANEOUSLY ACQUIRES DATA AT L, M, AND N, PROVIDING CRITICAL WAVELENGTH COVERAGE AT WAVELENGTHS WHERE PROTOPLANETS ARE EXPECTED TO PEAK IN BRIGHTNESS. THE CONTRACTOR WILL AUGMENT THE DATA FOR MORE NORTHERLY SYSTEMS USING THE LBTI, WHICH WILL PROVIDE ANGULAR RESOLUTION IN A SPECIFIC ORDER. GROUND-TRUTH FOR THE SHORTER WAVELENGTH INTERFEROMETRY WILL MAKE USE OF CONVENTIONAL L IMAGERY AND STATE OF THE ART OBSERVING AND DATA REDUCTION TECHNIQUES. THIS EFFORT WILL MAKE USE OF AVAILABLE ARCHIVAL DATA AND NEW OBSERVATIONS SUCH AS CAN BE OBTAINED AND WILL ALSO COMPARE THE IMAGERY WITH SPECTROSCOPIC OBSERVATIONS OF MOLECULAR GAS TO CONSTRAIN CAVITY SIZES AND IDENTIFY PLANETS, WHICH MAY HAVE CIRCUMPLANETARY DISKS. THIS EFFORT WILL ADVANCE KNOWLEDGE AND UNDERSTANDING OF EXOPLANETARY SYSTEMS BY PERFORMING NEW, UNIQUE OBSERVATIONS TO: (1) DETECT NEW PREVIOUSLY UNKNOWN YOUNG EXOPLANETS AND THEIR EFFECTS ON THEIR PARENT CIRCUMSTELLAR DISKS; (2) INTERPRET THE OBSERVATIONS BY COMPARING IMAGING AND SPECTROSCOPIC OBSERVATIONS AS WELL AS USING RADIATIVE TRANSFER MODELING TO OBTAIN THE PHYSICAL CONDITIONS IN THE DISKS; (3) AND IMPROVE OUR UNDERSTANDING OF THE ORIGINS OF EXOPLANETS."
