      "description": "IGF::OT::IGFNASAS EARTH SCIENCE TECHNOLOGY OFFICE HAS FUNDED A PHASE III EFFORT FOR FIBERTEK TO DEVELOP ANENGINEERING VERSION OF A UV LASER SUITABLE FOR FUTURE SPACEBASED REMOTE SENSING MEASUREMENTS WITHA GOAL OF ADVANCING THE LASER SYSTEM TO TRL 6. THE LASER HAS BEEN BUILT AND SHOWN TO MEET THE REQUIREDPERFORMANCE METRICS. LIFETIME TESTING AT FULL ENERGY AT 532 NM 125 MJ PULSE AT BOTH 532 NM AND 1064NM, 1.2 BILLION SHOTS AND HALF POWER AT 355 NM 50 MJ PULSE AT 355 NM BUT STILL 250 MJ PULSE TOTALENERGY, 1.5 BILLION SHOTS HAS DEMONSTRATED THE REQUIRED OPTICAL COMPONENT LIFETIME, BUT HAS SURFACEDTHE NEED FOR A BETTER UNDERSTANDING OF PROPER PUMP DIODE DERATING TO MEET THE DESIRED 14 BILLION SHOTLASER SYSTEM LIFETIME  A FACTOR OF 10 HIGHER THAN PERVIOUS MISSIONS DEMONSTRATED TECHNOLOGIES. THISPHASE III EFFORT LOOKS TO PERFORM ANALYSIS AND PREPARE FOR TESTING TO VERIFY THAT CURRENT DIODE PUMPTECHNOLOGY CAN SUPPORT THE>14 BILLION SHOT LIFETIME FOR THE HEUVD LASER. A MORE COMPLETE MODEL OFTHE HEUVD LASER IS ALSO SOUGHT TO BETTER QUANTIFY THE IMPACT OF DIODE DECAY ON THE 532 NM AND 355NM LASER OUTPUTS. PHASE III GOALS WILL BE ACHIEVED BY LEVERAGING PREVIOUS WORK FROM BOTH PHASE I ANDII STTRS AND SBIRS. THE PRIMARY STTR THAT IS BEING LEVERAGED, AND THAT WHICH WE LOOK TO LINK THISPHASE III CONTRACT TO IS THE RECENTLY COMPLETED PHASE I STTR ULTRA-COMPACT TRANSMITTER FOR SPACEBASED LIDAR CONTRACT NNX16CL43P. A KEY DEVELOPMENT FOR EXTENDING THE TECHNOLOGY FROM THISPROGRAM INTO FUTURE SPACE BASED MISSIONS IS AN IMPROVED QUANTITATIVE UNDERSTANDING OF HOW TO DE RATEPUMP DIODES IN ORDER TO ACHIEVE LIFETIMES 14 BILLION SHOTS."
