      "total_award_value": 38993,
      "description": "INTEGRATED MULTI-LAYER INSULATION (IMLI) IS A NEXT GENERATION MLI DEVELOPED BY QUEST THERMAL GROUP. IMLI USES PROPRIETARY DISCRETE SPACER TECHNOLOGY  WITH LOW THERMAL CONDUCTANCE MICROMOLDED POLYMER SPACERS TO REDUCE HEAT LEAK, CONTROL LAYER SPACING AND DENSITY, AND FORM A ROBUST BONDED-UP STRUCTURE. IMLI OFFERS HIGHER THERMAL PERFORMANCE THAN CONVENTIONAL MLI, IN A VERY ROBUST FULLY BONDED STRUCTURE, WITH LOW PARTICULATES FOR OPTICS (NO NETTING), PREDICTABLE AND REPEATABLE PERFORMANCE, AND POTENTIALLY FEWER LAYERS AND LOWER MASS THAN NETTING-BASED MLI. IMLI HAS FLOWN ON NASA S RRM3 FLIGHT EXPERIMENT AND IS AT TRL9. IMLI IS SCHEDULED TO FLY ON THE NASA/BALL AEROSPACE GREEN PROPELLANT INFUSION MISSION IN EARLY 2019. IMLI THERMAL PERFORMANCE HAS BEEN EXTENSIVELY TESTED VIA BOILOFF CALORIMETRY AT QUEST THERMAL GROUP, BALL AEROSPACE, NASA KSC CRYOGENICS TEST LAB ON THE C100 AND C500 CALORIMETERS, AND AT GLENN RESEARCH CENTER S NEW CALORIMETER. MARSHALL SPACE FLIGHT CENTER AND GRC HAVE TESTED THE LOAD BEARING MLI VARIANT ( SELF SUPPORTING IMLI ) IN THE RBO II LARGE SCALE LH2 BOILOFF REDUCTION TEST PROGRAM, VALIDATING THAT IT IS A VERY ROBUST INSULATION WITH LOWER HEAT FLUX THAN CONVENTIONAL MLI AND TANK STANDOFFS."
