      "description": "AS SMALLSATS BECOME THE  SATELLITE OF CHOICE  FOR NASA AND OTHER GOVERNMENT AND PRIVATE SPACE MISSIONS, THERE IS A GROWING NEED TO ENABLE SMALLSATS TO PERFORM  LONG BASELINE  AND  SPATIALLY DIVERSE  OBSERVATION, MEASUREMENT AND COLLECTION MISSIONS. TRADITIONALLY, THESE TYPES OF MISSIONS WOULD BE PERFORMED EITHER BY USING FORMATION FLYING OR BY USING  LARGE  SATELLITES EQUIPPED WITH COMPLEX / ADVANCE DEPLOYABLE STRUCTURES. THE PROPOSED  MAKERSAT DEMONSTRATION MISSION  EFFORT ADDRESSES A THIRD ALTERNATIVE FOR ACCOMPLISHING THIS CLASS OF MISSIONS: IN-SPACE MANUFACTURING  CONSTRUCTABLE  TECHNOLOGIES, THAT ALLOW SMALLSATS TO  GROW / EVOLVE  INTO SIGNIFICANTLY LARGER STRUCTURES. A SMALLSAT THAT ONCE ON ORBIT CAN INCREASE ITS SIZE FROM ONE TO TWO ORDERS OF MAGNITUDE PROVIDES AN EXCITING OPTION TO FORMATION FLYING OR DEPLOYABLE STRUCTURES. THE GOAL OF THE PROPOSED EFFORT IS TO DEVELOP A DEMONSTRATION MISSION THAT PROVES THE VIABILITY OF CONSTRUCTABLE TECHNOLOGIES AS AN ALTERNATIVE SOLUTION FOR  LONG BASELINE  AND  SPATIALLY DIVERSE  OBSERVATION, MEASUREMENT AND COLLECTION MISSIONS."
